T1  - Economic underdevelopment: The case of a missing market for human capital
AU  - Ljungqvist, Lars
JO  - Journal of Development Economics
VL  - 40
IS  - 2
SP  - 219
EP  - 239
PY  - 1993
DA  - 1993/04/01/
SN  - 0304-3878
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3878(93)90084-Z
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/030438789390084Z
AB  - This paper demonstrates that the coexistence of developed and underdeveloped countries can be a stationary equilibrium in a world economy with free trade in consumption goods and physical capital. An underdeveloped country is characterized by a high ratio of unskilled workers in the labor force, a small stock of physical capital, a low gross national product, a high rate of return on human capital and a corresponding large wage differential between skilled and unskilled workers. The critical assumptions are that future labor earnings cannot serve as collateral on a loan and indivisibilities in education.
